│ The issue is a persistent crash in the SLP vectorizer due to an invalid shuffle mask. My previous attempts to patch the `peekThroughShuffles` function have failed, │
│ even after correcting for syntax errors and corrupted source files. The crash remains, indicating a fundamental flaw in my approach.                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ The core problem is that an invalid shuffle mask is being created and used. My fix attempts have focused on adding a check inside `peekThroughShuffles` to validate │
│ the mask *after* it's composed. However, the crash occurs in a call to `isIdentityMask` at the very beginning of the `peekThroughShuffles` loop, before my check is │
│ ever reached. This means the `Mask` parameter is already invalid when `peekThroughShuffles` is called.                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ The invalid mask is created in the caller, `BaseShuffleAnalysis::createShuffle`. This function builds a `NewMask` and passes it to `peekThroughShuffles`. The logic │
│ for building `NewMask` seems to be the source of the problem. It iterates through a set of values and populates the mask. If a value is not a vector, it's treated  │
│ as a vector of size 1, and the mask index is set to 0. However, if the first value (`V1`) is a vector, the mask indices for subsequent scalar values are not        │
│ correctly offset, leading to out-of-bounds indices relative to `V1`'s size.                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ To fix this, I will modify the mask generation logic in `createShuffle`. I will introduce a `Lane` counter. When processing scalar values, instead of always using  │
│ index 0, I will use the current `Lane` value and increment it. This ensures that each scalar is assigned a unique and correct lane in the vector being constructed, │
│ preventing the creation of an invalid shuffle mask.                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
